 <p>A period is a release of blood from a girl's <a href=3D"https://kidshea=
lth.org/en/teens/female-repro.html">uterus</a>, out through her vagina. It =
is a sign that she is getting close to the end of <a href=3D"https://kidshe=
alth.org/en/teens/puberty.html">puberty</a>.&nbsp;It also means that she ca=
n get pregnant if she has sex.</p>=20
<p>There is a lot to learn about periods. Here are answers to some common q=
uestions.</p>=20
<h3>When Do Periods Usually Start?</h3>=20
<p>Most girls get their first period when they're around 12.&nbsp;But somet=
imes it comes a few years earlier or later. Every girl's body has its own s=
chedule.</p>=20
<p>There isn't one right age for a girl to get her period. But signs to wat=
ch for include:</p>=20
<ul>=20
 <li>breasts starting to develop (periods usually start about 2 years after=
 this)</li>=20
 <li>hair growing under a girl's arms and in her private parts</li>=20
 <li>seeing or feeling <a href=3D"https://kidshealth.org/en/teens/vdischarg=
e2.html">vaginal discharge</a> fluid (sort of like mucus), which usually be=
gins about 6 months to a year before a girl gets her first period</li>=20
</ul>=20
<h3>What Causes a Period?</h3>=20
<p>A period happens because of changes in <a class=3D"definition" href=3D"h=
ttps://kidshealth.org/en/teens/menstruation.html#" aria-disabled=3D"true" a=
ria-describedby=3D"msg_hormones_T" id=3D"hormones_T" data-left=3D"349.20312=
5" data-top=3D"884">hormones</a>
 in the body. Hormones are chemical messengers. The ovaries release the fem=
ale hormones <a class=3D"definition" href=3D"https://kidshealth.org/en/teen=
s/menstruation.html#" aria-disabled=3D"true" aria-describedby=3D"msg_estrog=
en_T" id=3D"estrogen_T" data-left=3D"456.875" data-top=3D"908">estrogen</a>
 and <a class=3D"definition" href=3D"https://kidshealth.org/en/teens/menstr=
uation.html#" aria-disabled=3D"true" aria-describedby=3D"msg_progesterone_T=
" id=3D"progesterone_T" data-left=3D"570.25" data-top=3D"908">progesterone<=
/a>
 , which cause the lining of the uterus (or womb) to build up. The built-up=
 lining is ready for a fertilized egg (an egg that has joined with a sperm)=
 to attach to and develop into a baby. If there is no fertilized egg, the l=
ining breaks down and bleeds. Then the same process happens all over again.=
</p>




=09



   =20


</div>
