 <p>It usually takes about a month for the lining to build up, then break d=
own. That is why most females get their periods around once a month.</p>=20
<h3>How Does Ovulation Relate to Periods?</h3>=20
<p><strong>Ovulation</strong>&nbsp;(pronounced: ov-yoo-LAY-shun) is the rel=
ease of an egg from the ovaries. The same hormones that cause the uterus li=
ning to build up also cause an egg to leave one of the ovaries. The egg tra=
vels through a thin tube called a fallopian tube to the uterus.</p>=20
<p>If the egg is fertilized by a sperm cell, it attaches to the wall of the=
 uterus, where over time it develops into a baby. If the egg is not fertili=
zed, the uterus lining breaks down and bleeds, causing a period.</p>=20
<h3>Do Periods Happen Regularly When Menstruation Starts?</h3>=20
<p>For the first few years after a girl starts her period, it might not <a =
href=3D"https://kidshealth.org/en/teens/irregular-periods.html">come regula=
rly</a>. This is normal at first. By about 2=E2=80=933 years after her firs=
t period, a girl's periods should be coming around once every 4=E2=80=935 w=
eeks.</p>=20
<h3>Can a Girl Get Pregnant as Soon as Her Period Starts?</h3>=20
<p>Yes, a girl can get pregnant as soon as her period starts. A girl can ev=
en get pregnant right <a href=3D"https://kidshealth.org/en/teens/pre-period=
.html">before her very first period</a> because her hormones might already =
be active. The hormones may have led to ovulation and the building of the u=
terine wall. If so and the girl has sex, she can get pregnant, even though =
she has never had a period.</p>=20
<h3>How Long Do Periods Last?</h3>=20
<p>Periods usually last about 5 days. But a period can be shorter or last l=
onger.</p>=20
<h3>How Often Does a Period Happen?</h3>=20
<p>Periods usually happen about once every 4=E2=80=935 weeks. But some girl=
s get their periods a little less or more often.</p>=20
<h3>Should I Use a Pad, Tampon, or Menstrual Cup?</h3>=20
<p>You have <a href=3D"https://kidshealth.org/en/teens/supplies.html">many =
choices</a> about how to deal with period blood. You may need to experiment=
 a bit to find which works best for you. Some girls use only one method and=
 others switch between different methods.</p>=20
<ul>=20
 <li>Most girls use <strong>pads</strong> when they first get their period.=
 Pads are made of cotton and come in lots of different sizes and shapes. Th=
ey have sticky strips that attach to the underwear.</li>=20
 <li>Many girls find <strong>tampons</strong>&nbsp;more convenient than pad=
s, especially when playing sports or swimming. A tampon is a cotton plug th=
at you put into your vagina. Most tampons come with an applicator that guid=
es the tampon into place. The tampon absorbs the blood. Don't leave a tampo=
n in for more than 8 hours because this can increase your risk of a serious=
 infection called <a href=3D"https://kidshealth.org/en/teens/tss.html">toxi=
c shock syndrome</a>.</li>=20
 <li>Some girls prefer a <strong>menstrual cup</strong>. Most are made of s=
ilicone. To use a menstrual cup, a girl inserts it into her vagina. It hold=
s the blood until she empties it.</li>=20
</ul>=20
<h3>How Much Blood Comes Out?</h3>=20
<p>It may look like a lot of blood, but a girl usually only loses a few tab=
lespoons of blood during the whole period. Most girls need to change their =
pad, tampon, or menstrual cup about 3=E2=80=926 times a day.</p>=20
<h3>Will I Have Periods for the Rest of My Life?</h3>=20
<p>When women reach menopause (around age 45=E2=80=9255), their periods wil=
l permanently stop. Periods also stop during&nbsp;<a href=3D"https://kidshe=
alth.org/en/teens/pregnancy.html">pregnancy</a>.</p>=20
<h3>What Is PMS?</h3>=20
<p><a href=3D"https://kidshealth.org/en/parents/menstrual-problems.html">PM=
S (premenstrual syndrome)</a> is when emotional and physical symptoms happe=
n before or during a girl's period. These can include moodiness, sadness, a=
nxiety, bloating, and acne. The symptoms go away after the first few days o=
f a period.</p>=20
<h3>What Can I Do About Cramps?</h3>=20
<p>Many girls have <a href=3D"https://kidshealth.org/en/teens/cramps.html">=
cramps</a> with their period, especially in the first few days. If cramps b=
other you, you can try:</p>=20
<ul>=20
 <li>a warm heating pad on your belly</li>=20
 <li>taking ibuprofen (Advil, Motrin, or store brand) or naproxen (Aleve or=
 store brand)</li>=20
</ul>=20
<h3>When Should I Call the Doctor?</h3>=20
<p>Most girls don't have any problems with their periods. But call your doc=
tor if you:</p>=20
<ul>=20
 <li>are 15 and haven't started your period</li>=20
 <li>have had your period for more than 2 years and it's <a href=3D"https:/=
/kidshealth.org/en/teens/still-irregular.html">still not regular</a> (comin=
g about every 4=E2=80=935 weeks)</li>=20
 <li>have bleeding between periods</li>=20
 <li>have severe cramps that don't get better with ibuprofen or naproxen&nb=
sp;</li>=20
 <li>have very heavy bleeding (bleeding that goes through a pad or tampon f=
aster than every 1 hour)</li>=20
 <li>have periods that last more than about a week</li>=20
 <li>have severe PMS that gets in the way of your everyday activities</li>=
=20
</ul>=20
<h3>What Else Should I Know?</h3>=20
<p>Periods are a natural, healthy part of life. They shouldn't get in the w=
ay of exercising, having fun, and enjoying life. If you have questions abou=
t periods, ask your doctor, a parent, health teacher, school nurse, or olde=
r sister.</p>




=09



